<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<!--
  Hardened-runtime entitlements for the signed PersonalDB.app + its frozen
  daemon sidecar (see sign-and-notarize.sh). Hardened runtime is required
  for notarization; these three exceptions are required *in addition* to
  it because the payload is a python-build-standalone CPython interpreter,
  not a normal compiled Mach-O app:

  - allow-jit / allow-unsigned-executable-memory: CPython's own bytecode
    interpreter (and any C-extension that JITs, e.g. some numeric/crypto
    libs) writes to and executes from memory it allocated at runtime.
    Hardened runtime blocks W^X-violating executable memory by default;
    without these two, the interpreter can crash or refuse to start.
  - disable-library-validation: hardened runtime otherwise requires every
    dylib a signed binary loads to be signed by the *same* Team ID. CPython
    dlopens compiled extension modules (.so files) from site-packages at
    import time, and those are ordinary Python-ecosystem wheels signed (if
    at all) by whoever built them, not us. Without this, `import ssl`,
    `import cryptography`, etc. fail under a hardened-runtime-signed
    interpreter.

  This is a real (if unavoidable) reduction in hardened runtime's
  protection, but it's the standard tradeoff every frozen-Python-as-a-signed-
  macOS-app project makes (PyInstaller/py2app apps that embed C extensions
  all need the same three). Scope stays as narrow as the plan allows: no
  other entitlements (no network-client sandboxing exception needed since
  this app isn't sandboxed at all (App Store distribution is explicitly
  out of scope, see packaging/README.md), and no camera/mic/etc entries).
-->
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
    <key>com.apple.security.cs.allow-jit</key>
    <true/>
    <key>com.apple.security.cs.allow-unsigned-executable-memory</key>
    <true/>
    <key>com.apple.security.cs.disable-library-validation</key>
    <true/>
</dict>
</plist>
